National Security Advisor Tom Donilon visited Japan on July 26 and had a positive and productive meeting with Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda and other senior officials. They discussed cooperation between the U.S. and Japan in various fields, emphasizing the strategic importance of their alliance and the need for continued coordination on political, economic, and security issues. Donilon also highlighted the importance of cooperation on North Korea, Iran, and regional security in Asia. He discussed the development of regional institutions like the East Asia Summit and welcomed Japan's interest in joining the Trans-Pacific Partnership. Donilon expressed appreciation for Japan's support for Afghanistan and its successful hosting of the Tokyo Donors Conference.